tion and diseases such as diphtheria, beriberi, dysentery, and tuberculosis afflicted all these unfortunate men, affecting their lives not only in the camps during the war but after they returned home. Yet despite the dispiriting circumstances of their captivity, these men found ways to improve their existence, keeping up their morale with such events as musical concerts and entertainments created entirely within the various camps. Based largely on hundreds of interviews with former POWs, as well as material culled from archives around the world, Professor Roland details the extremes the prisoners endured — from having to eat fattened maggots in order to live to choosing starvation by trading away their skimpy rations for cigarettes. No previous book has shown the essential relationship between almost universal ill health and POW life and death, or provides such a complete and unbiased account of POW life in the Far East in the 1940s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGuerre mondiale, 1939-1945xPrisonniers et prisons des Japonais. 0aGuerre mondiale, 1939-1945xSoins médicauxxJapon. 0aPrisoners of warxChinaxHong Kong. 0aPrisoners of warxHealth and hygienexJapan. 0aPrisoners of warxHealth and hygienezJapan. 0aPrisoners of warxJapan. 0aPrisoners of warzChinazHong Kong. 0aPrisoners of warzJapan. 0aPrisonniers de guerrexChinexHong Kong. 0aPrisonniers de guerrexJapon. 0aPrisonniers de guerrexSanté et hygiènexJapon. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xMedical carexJapan. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xMedical carezJapan. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPrisoners and prisons, Japanese. 4aHistory. 4aHistory: Military History. 4aMedical. 4aMedical: History Of Medicine. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z97831112741640